Got it—here are **minimal, targeted changes** you can drop in so long titles wrap cleanly, the hero is shorter on the blog + post pages only, and the filter/search controls don’t overflow on very small screens.

---

## 1) Long titles in the hero: allow wrapping + add comfortable measure

Right now `.hero-title` is forced into a single line (it uses `white-space: nowrap;` and `text-overflow: ellipsis`). Rather than changing that globally (it may be desirable on `index.html`), we’ll scope the fix to your blog listing and individual post pages.

**What to do**

1) **Add a modifier class** to the hero on `blog.html` and the post page(s):
```html
<!-- blog.html / single-post.html -->
<section class="hero hero--slim hero--wrap">
  <div class="hero-content">
    <h1 class="hero-title">…long blog post title goes here…</h1>
    …
  </div>
</section>
```
> If you prefer to avoid touching the hero class, you can instead put a page flag on `<body>` and use `.page--blog` / `.page--post`. See the CSS below (both are supported).

2) **Append this CSS at the end** of `assets/css/tuition-css-1.0.0.css` (place it after the existing hero rules so it wins the cascade):

```css
/* ---------- BLOG & POST: wrap long hero titles ---------- */
.hero--wrap .hero-title,
.page--blog .hero .hero-title,
.page--post .hero .hero-title {
  /* turn off single-line truncation */
  white-space: normal;
  overflow: visible;
  text-overflow: clip;

  /* robust wrapping for long words / URLs */
  overflow-wrap: anywhere;   /* modern */
  word-break: break-word;    /* Safari safety */
  hyphens: auto;             /* needs lang="en" on <html> (you have it) */

  /* comfortable reading measure + side padding */
  max-width: 72ch;
  margin-inline: clamp(12px, 4vw, 32px);
}
```

---

## 2) Make the hero **shorter** on `blog.html` and post pages (keep top spacing intact)

Your current `.hero` has a fairly generous `min-height` meant for the homepage. We’ll keep the homepage as-is and only slim it down for the blog and posts. We won’t touch the top spacing; we’ll just reduce `min-height` and trim the **bottom** padding a bit.

**Append to the same CSS file (below the block above):**
```css
/* ---------- BLOG & POST: slimmer hero ---------- */
.hero.hero--slim,
.page--blog .hero,
.page--post .hero {
  min-height: clamp(220px, 24vw, 360px);
  padding-bottom: clamp(8px, 2vw, 20px); /* keep top look, trim bottom */
}

/* tighten further on phones, still keeping the top look intact */
@media (max-width: 767.98px) {
  .hero.hero--slim,
  .page--blog .hero,
  .page--post .hero {
    min-height: clamp(200px, 40vw, 300px);
  }
}
```

> This is deliberately **scoped** so `index.html` keeps its current hero height. Use either the `hero--slim` class on the section or page-level classes on `<body>` (both selectors are present above).

---

## 3) Under 380px wide screens: stop the search + selectors + “Apply” from overflowing

On very narrow devices (320–375 px), flex items often refuse to shrink unless you explicitly allow it, and keeping them in a single row is counterproductive. We’ll make the controls wrap by default and **stack them to full‑width** under 380 px. To avoid relying on a specific wrapper name from your earlier scaffold, the CSS covers a few common wrappers; add **one** of these classes to the container that holds your search, the three `<select>`s, and the Apply button (recommended: `blog-controls`).

**HTML (minimal addition):**
```html
<!-- around the search field + 3 selects + Apply -->
<form class="blog-controls" …>
  …
</form>
```

**CSS to append (after the blocks above):**
```css
/* ---------- Blog filter controls: responsive + no overflow ---------- */

/* 1) Let controls wrap on small/medium widths */
.blog-controls,
.blog-filters,
.post-filters {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 8px;
  align-items: center;
}

/* 2) Allow shrinking inside flex row (critical on iOS Safari) */
.blog-controls input[type="search"],
.blog-controls select,
.blog-controls button,
.blog-filters input[type="search"],
.blog-filters select,
.blog-filters button,
.post-filters input[type="search"],
.post-filters select,
.post-filters button {
  min-width: 0; /* without this, controls may refuse to shrink */
}

/* 3) On very small phones, stack everything to full width */
@media (max-width: 379.98px) {
  .blog-controls,
  .blog-filters,
  .post-filters {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
  .blog-controls input[type="search"],
  .blog-controls select,
  .blog-controls button,
  .blog-filters input[type="search"],
  .blog-filters select,
  .blog-filters button,
  .post-filters input[type="search"],
  .post-filters select,
  .post-filters button {
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

That’s intentionally terse and “defensive”:  
- `min-width: 0` solves the common **flex item can’t shrink** issue on Safari.  
- The `@media (max-width: 379.98px)` rule stacks items vertically so nothing is truncated.  
- If your current wrapper already uses `.blog-filters` or `.post-filters`, keep it; otherwise, adding `.blog-controls` is a one‑line, non‑breaking change.

---

## 4) “Contact” section copy‑paste readiness

You don’t need extra scaffolding. When you’re ready, you can paste a contact block above the footer in `blog.html` and post pages and it will inherit your existing section styles:

```html
<section class="section" id="contact">
  <!-- your contact markup -->
</section>
```

The `.section` class in your CSS already supplies spacing, centering, and responsive behavior, so it will drop in cleanly.

