Yep—this is almost always a too-tight `line-height` (sometimes compounded by a container with fixed height). Here’s a **minimal, safe patch** that fixes descender clipping on **non-blog pages** without touching your blog overrides.

### Add to the **end** of `assets/css/tuition-css-1.0.0.css`
```css
/* --- Fix descender clipping in hero titles on non-blog pages --- */
.hero .hero-title{
  /* give glyphs with descenders (g,j,p,q,y) headroom */
  line-height: 1.15;          /* was effectively ~1.00; bump slightly */
  padding-bottom: 0.12em;     /* tiny breathing room, visually neutral */
}

/* If a container is clipping, ensure the text can render fully */
.hero .hero-content{
  overflow: visible;          /* safe for text; does not affect background */
}
```

**Why this works**
- The tiny `line-height` bump prevents the glyph box from colliding with the container baseline.
- The `padding-bottom` adds a visually imperceptible cushion, covering font/platform quirks (some fonts have tight descender metrics).
- `overflow: visible` on `.hero-content` guards against any accidental clipping if an ancestor had `overflow: hidden`.

**Scope**
- This lives in your **base CSS** so it applies to the “other” (non-blog) pages.  
- Your blog pages already override hero behavior via `blog.css`, so nothing there changes.

If you still see clipping on a specific breakpoint/font size, increase `line-height` to `1.18` or `1.2`—but the values above usually solve it without altering the look.

Absolutely. We’ll keep this scoped to **single-post pages only** (so the listing grid isn’t affected) by targeting `.post` / `.post-body`, which only exist on `blog-post.html`.

Add the block below to the **end** of `assets/css/blog.css`, then bump the href to `?v=1.0.4` in `blog-post.html` to bust caches.

```css
/* ==============================================
   Single-post typography & spacing (blog-post.html)
   Version: 1.0.4
   ============================================== */

/* Narrower, more comfortable reading measure + side gutters */
.post{
  /* slightly narrower than listing cards => bigger margins */
  max-width: 68ch;                 /* was 70ch */
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding-inline: clamp(12px, 5vw, 32px); /* responsive side padding */
}

/* Body text: a bit larger than footer, with generous leading */
.post-body{
  font-size: clamp(1.05rem, 0.98rem + 0.38vw, 1.2rem); /* ~10–20% larger */
  line-height: 1.7;
}

/* Vertical rhythm for common elements */
.post-body p{ margin: 0 0 0.95em; }
.post-body ul,
.post-body ol{ margin: 0.6em 0 1.1em 1.35em; }
.post-body li + li{ margin-top: 0.35em; }

/* Headings: scale cleanly, with consistent spacing */
.post-body h2{
  font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 1.1rem + 1.2vw, 1.75rem);
  line-height: 1.25;
  margin: 1.2em 0 0.5em;
}
.post-body h3{
  font-size: clamp(1.18rem, 1.02rem + 0.8vw, 1.45rem);
  line-height: 1.3;
  margin: 1.1em 0 0.45em;
}
.post-body h4{
  font-size: clamp(1.08rem, 0.98rem + 0.5vw, 1.25rem);
  line-height: 1.35;
  margin: 1em 0 0.4em;
}

/* Media and pre/code already scale; add breathing room */
.post-body :is(img, video, iframe){
  display: block;
  margin: 0.9em auto;
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}
.post-body pre{
  font-size: 0.95em;               /* stays legible without overflowing */
  line-height: 1.5;
  padding: 12px;
  border-radius: 8px;
}

/* Blockquotes: subtle emphasis without heaviness */
.post-body blockquote{
  margin: 1em 0;
  padding: 0.25em 0.9em;
  border-inline-start: 4px solid var(--divider);
  opacity: 0.95;
}
```

### What changed (and why)
- **`.post`** now caps content at **68ch** and adds responsive side padding → visually larger margins/whitespace without breaking mobile.
- **`.post-body`** font size uses `clamp()` so it scales smoothly from small devices to desktops, ending ~10–20% larger than your base/footer text.
- Headings/lists get consistent margins so blocks don’t feel cramped.
- Kept everything **mobile-responsive**—on very narrow screens you’ll still have full-width content with readable sizes.

No HTML edits needed; just bump the CSS version in `blog-post.html`:

